              p
               {\textless} 0.02,
              r
               = 0.72). Relationships were strengthened when emotions were linked to perceptions of overall biodiversity (
              p
               {\textless} 0.001,
              r
               = 0.89). So, when participants thought the site was wildlife rich, they reported more positive emotions, even when actual avian biodiversity levels were not necessarily enhanced. The data strengthens the arguments that nature enhances well-being through positive affect, and that increased ‘engagement with nature’ may help support human health within urban environments. The results have strong implications for city planning with respect to the design, management and use of city green spaces.},
